, however, the Zhuang did not share a common ethnic identity. Katherine Palmer Kaup explores why the CCP in effect created the Zhuang nationality. Why did it launch a massive propaganda campaign to increase nationality consciousness? How is the party now responding to the Zhuang's assertive political demands? This pioneering study unveils the unique culture of the Zhuang people, showing at the same time the CCP's skillful balancing of ethnic and regional loyalties over the past 50 years to integrate the diversity of China's ethnic mosaic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aZhuang (Chinese people). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311078426840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637322840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626373228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626373228/original  a978-3-11-078426-8  Lynne Rienner Press Complete Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK